The paper deals with an online matching problem, which is a classic topic in computer science and falls under the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also involves game theory (cs.GT) as it analyzes the competitive ratio of the algorithm. The use of algorithms to solve real-world problems such as ride-sharing and real-estate agency suggests that the paper may also fall under the categories of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and social and information networks (cs.SI). Finally, the paper uses a randomized primal dual technique, which is a common tool in machine learning (cs.LG).
